WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.840
[Amit Varma]: Being a writer is an act of immense arrogance. Very few people write as a means of catharsis

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:14.320
[Amit Varma]: or self-expression. Most people who write want to be read and in their act of writing,

00:00:14.320 --> 00:00:19.840
[Amit Varma]: therefore, is a presumption that what they are writing brings value to somebody's life.

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:23.760
[Amit Varma]: Think about it. Every time somebody reads an article written by you, they do so when they

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:27.840
[Amit Varma]: could be doing a million other things with their time. There's an opportunity cost to their time.

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:33.280
[Amit Varma]: Time is money. And yet you simply assume that when you write something, that is worth that time.

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:39.840
[Amit Varma]: This is often arrogant and sometimes delusional. And it's also true of podcasting. You're listening

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:45.040
[Amit Varma]: to me speaking right now when you could be doing so many other things. Is this worth your time?

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:53.040
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics,

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:59.280
[Unknown]: politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. I'm an accidental podcaster. And when I started The

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.040
[Amit Varma]: Seen and The Unseen, I assumed that at worst, I'll get laughed at. At best, I'll get ignored.

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:12.960
[Amit Varma]: But hey, what the hell new experience? Well, I've grown to enjoy podcasting, though I've sometimes

00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:17.920
[Amit Varma]: felt that I'm doing this in a vacuum. Our numbers are decent for a podcast. But why do people listen

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:22.240
[Amit Varma]: to this? What do they think of the show? What could I be doing better? Also, is there any way

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:27.760
[Amit Varma]: that instead of me asking questions, once in a while, I have to answer them and tough ones at

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:34.000
[Amit Varma]: that? I do the show in partnership with IBM podcast. We each own 50% of the show. And one

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.120
[Amit Varma]: of the people who works here, Kavita Rajvare, recently mentioned that she met some people at

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:43.600
[Amit Varma]: her music class who are regular listeners of The Seen and The Unseen. So why don't I do an episode

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:47.440
[Amit Varma]: where I interact with them? I thought this was a good idea. It gave me a chance to see if such

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:51.840
[Amit Varma]: people actually existed. I mean, who listens to the show, and maybe get some feedback from them.

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:58.560
[Amit Varma]: And I could expand this into an AMA or an ask me anything. Now, conducting an AMA for myself

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.960
[Amit Varma]: itself feels embarrassing because I'm not a celebrity or a man of great accomplishment.

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:07.840
[Amit Varma]: But I spent so much time pontificating on the world that I thought it would be nice to open

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:12.560
[Amit Varma]: myself up to questions, including difficult ones. I put out a call on Twitter and Facebook,

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:17.840
[Amit Varma]: and my noble producer, the famous stand up comic Abbas Momin has compiled all those questions and

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:23.440
[Amit Varma]: will shoot them at me. But before that, a warm welcome to my guests on the show, Nakul Sanpurkar

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:28.080
[Amit Varma]: and Rachit Jain. Nakul and Rachit, welcome to the show. Thanks, Amit. Glad to be here.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:33.040
[Unknown]: Thanks, Amit. Glad to be here. From a listener to now, right here with you. It's great.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:37.680
[Amit Varma]: Right. So before you start asking, I'm just like curious how people listen to podcasts. You know,

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:42.000
[Amit Varma]: when when I first started podcasting, the reason I called myself an accidental podcaster was

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
[Amit Varma]: I never considered podcasting because I never listened to podcasts. I was not one of those

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.920
[Amit Varma]: people who would listen to podcasts. And so it was it was completely new for me. And of course,

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:56.880
[Amit Varma]: since I've started podcasting, I listen a lot. But do you guys listen to podcasts a lot, Nakul?

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:02.480
[Unknown]: Yeah, actually, this is I was introduced to podcasts by my brother in the US. When I went

00:03:02.480 --> 00:03:08.080
[Unknown]: to visit him, I would see him, you know, listening to podcasts on his commute a lot.

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:13.360
[Unknown]: And that's when I got hooked on to those podcasts. And next thing you know, I've come back to India,

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:18.080
[Unknown]: I'm listening to those podcasts and looking for, you know, podcasts based in India on Indian issues

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:22.800
[Unknown]: on Indian things. And so that's when I was introduced to IBM and seen and unseen. And

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:27.360
[Unknown]: that's when I became a regular listener. So for me, it was more like I had been listening

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:32.400
[Unknown]: to podcasts on and off for the last two, three years, but largely centric to comedy,

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:38.320
[Unknown]: where you know, comedians do do a podcast, a lot of varied stuff, etc. But I guess with respect to

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:44.320
[Unknown]: IBM and CNN, Nakul is the one who introduced a lot of us to it. And yeah, but in terms of

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:50.480
[Unknown]: consumption, it's more or less on our way to work. I was fed up of listening to music, how much more

00:03:50.480 --> 00:03:55.920
[Unknown]: music can listen to all day, right? So podcast is like a breath of fresh air coming in while you're

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:59.520
[Unknown]: on your way to work or going back. It's the best utilization of time I can do.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:04.960
[Amit Varma]: Right. So I'm just delaying the inevitable. You guys have some tough questions for me. Shoot.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:12.320
[Unknown]: So, since I'm a regular listener here, I've always seen that, you know, we've most of the

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:19.200
[Unknown]: episodes are focused on the bad, quote unquote, policymaking or decisions that governments have

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:25.200
[Unknown]: taken, you know, like demonetization or jobs or pakoda now makes etc. So what do you think has

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:29.280
[Unknown]: been a good policy decision by any previous government? And what do you think have been the

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:33.680
[Amit Varma]: seen and the unseen benefits of those? Okay, that's a great question. I'll

00:04:33.680 --> 00:04:37.520
[Amit Varma]: have to actually think a bit for that. We are going in cold. So I haven't seen these questions

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:43.360
[Amit Varma]: before. I think, firstly, the reason I tend to focus on, and everybody, in fact, tends to focus

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:46.960
[Amit Varma]: on policies which have a negative effect is those negative effects are unseen. And therefore, you

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:51.520
[Amit Varma]: feel a sort of a duty to point out that no, hey, this looks good. This has great intentions. But

00:04:51.520 --> 00:05:01.440
[Amit Varma]: these are the kind of effects it can have. As for having good effects. I would say that I can't

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:04.880
[Amit Varma]: think of something offhand and you've studied public policy. So maybe you can help me. But

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:10.560
[Amit Varma]: anything that I think, increases freedom, increases economic freedom, or increases personal freedoms

00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:17.920
[Amit Varma]: for that matter, will inevitably have good effects, which are often hard to quantify. I mean, okay,

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:23.120
[Amit Varma]: here's an easy quantification, which people often give you look at the different fates of Eastern

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:28.400
[Amit Varma]: West Germany, when they chose a different baskets of public policy that they chose at the separation

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:33.280
[Amit Varma]: and ditto North and South Korea, they chose consciously to go in different directions and

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:37.280
[Amit Varma]: follow different kinds of policies. And you saw the impact of what economic freedom did

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:43.040
[Amit Varma]: in West Germany and South Korea, and the ravages that were brought upon the people of East Germany

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.560
[Amit Varma]: and North Korea as a result of their taking the wrong direction. So I guess that's one example.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:51.600
[Amit Varma]: While this episode goes on, if I think of something, I'll bring it up. But

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:57.120
[Amit Varma]: yeah, I mean, this one tends to keep focusing on all the things government does wrong,

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.680
[Amit Varma]: because it does so much wrong. Yeah, absolutely.

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:06.800
[Unknown]: So yeah, my question comes out of a recent Pragati podcast, which was related to podcasts

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:11.760
[Unknown]: itself, right? About how this entire issue of, you know, discoverability is there. Podcasts are not

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:16.960
[Unknown]: so big in India right now. And as a alternative content source, it's still very, very low,

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:22.240
[Unknown]: right? People listen to music, videos, etc. So what is your take on that in terms of, you know,

00:06:22.240 --> 00:06:27.600
[Unknown]: we obviously far lagging behind in terms of the indicators in the US for that. But what will

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:33.840
[Unknown]: it require in India to change that, you know, behavioral shift for consuming podcasts as an

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:38.240
[Amit Varma]: alternative platform? Great question. I should tell those of my listeners who are wondering

00:06:38.240 --> 00:06:42.560
[Amit Varma]: what Rachit is referring to. This is an episode of the Pragati podcast, which is a great show hosted

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:47.840
[Amit Varma]: by Pawan Srinath and Hamsini Harihar and my colleagues at Pragati. And they spoke to Amit

00:06:47.840 --> 00:06:53.760
[Amit Varma]: Doshi of IBM podcast. And it's a very enlightening conversation. So just check that out either on

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:58.720
[Amit Varma]: the IBM app or on thinkpragati.com. But to answer your question, I think here's the thing. India

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:04.800
[Amit Varma]: doesn't have a culture of talk radio, that much is, which is why even I was very skeptical of

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:10.240
[Amit Varma]: podcasts. You know, I was an early blogger, 1516 years ago, but I was not an early podcaster,

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:14.400
[Amit Varma]: because I thought Kon sunta hai. And I assumed that that's a cultural thing that talk radio is

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:19.120
[Amit Varma]: big in the US and whatever, but in India, it simply isn't. Now, Amit, when he was, Amit Doshi,

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:25.120
[Amit Varma]: when he was trying to convince me to do this show, or to do a show with him, his spiel to me was that

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:30.400
[Amit Varma]: look, research has shown across the world, across cultures, 30% of the people who listen to audio

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:36.080
[Amit Varma]: content prefer talk to music, 30%. And because these are findings from across the world and

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:40.800
[Amit Varma]: across cultures, that means that there's something hardwired, that a certain number of us just

00:07:40.800 --> 00:07:47.360
[Amit Varma]: prefer talk to music, which is and 30% doesn't seem like much, but 30% of a lot of people is a

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:54.560
[Amit Varma]: lot. And so therefore, then that raises a question, why hasn't talk taken off in India. And one reason

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:59.600
[Amit Varma]: for this is that there's just been a vicious cycle, where no one's tried to supply it. And

00:07:59.600 --> 00:08:03.360
[Amit Varma]: therefore, there haven't been listeners. And because there haven't been listeners, no one's

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:09.520
[Amit Varma]: tried to supply it. And what I think IBM podcast is doing with Amit and so on is trying to break

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:15.280
[Amit Varma]: that and saying that no, you know, screw what the numbers are right now. I'm going to try and give

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:22.000
[Amit Varma]: you great audio content with all these variety of different shows. And, and let's build an audience

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.560
[Amit Varma]: and basically try to break that vicious circle and turn it into a virtuous circle, right? So people

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:32.400
[Unknown]: just just to add on there. So for you personally, then, you know, let's say Amit Doshi is doing a

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:35.920
[Unknown]: fantastic job, obviously bringing content to all of us. But for you personally, you know,

00:08:35.920 --> 00:08:40.880
[Unknown]: you spoke about opportunity cost, right? For you as well, you could be writing another, you know,

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:44.960
[Unknown]: column somewhere, or you know, you can be writing another book and devoting your time towards that.

00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:49.840
[Unknown]: What made you, you know, say you said that, you know, one of the factors was this entire data,

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:54.000
[Unknown]: which you had in front of you that, you know, people will listen, but to get into the industry

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.720
[Amit Varma]: at such a nascent stage, what made you do that? Right. So like I said, I was an accidental

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:02.560
[Amit Varma]: podcaster. So what really happened was, there's a very, very close friend of mine, a dear friend

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:07.280
[Amit Varma]: of mine called Naren Shannoy. And Naren Shannoy hosts a show called Simplified with Deepak

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Gopalakrishnan. Right now, they have a third co host, but it was a two of them when they started.

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And they started on their own, they weren't with IBM. And one day, one of them put up something

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.760
[Amit Varma]: on Facebook saying that, hey, we've joined up with IBM, and we are doing this and all that.

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:24.560
[Amit Varma]: And I just put a note of congratulations, at which point Amit replied to my comment, Amit Doshi,

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:28.000
[Amit Varma]: and said that, you know, a few months ago, I approached you and said, would you be interested

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.560
[Amit Varma]: in a podcast? And you said, No, you think you'd be interested now. And I absolutely didn't remember

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:36.320
[Amit Varma]: anyone approaching me. But my attitude towards podcasts was very condescending, like who the

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:40.960
[Amit Varma]: hell is trying to listen, screw this. So, so I said, Yeah, okay, let's talk. And we met up and

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:46.080
[Amit Varma]: all that. And I told him that one idea I had for a TV show at this time was a scene in the unseen.

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:49.840
[Amit Varma]: The scene in the unseen, by the way, is based on a famous essay by Frederick Bastia,

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:54.800
[Amit Varma]: that which is seen and that which is not seen, where he talks about a particular public policy

00:09:54.800 --> 00:09:58.800
[Amit Varma]: and why everyone praises it, but you need to look at the unseen effects. So I thought that's a great

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:04.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of framework to look at the whole world by. Like Henry Hazlitt wrote a great book a few

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:08.800
[Amit Varma]: decades ago called economics in one lesson, which just looked at different aspects of the economy

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:12.880
[Amit Varma]: through this framework. So I said, Look, here's an idea I had for TV. And he said, Why don't you

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:16.720
[Amit Varma]: do a podcast? And I said, Okay, and here's the thing, when you speak of opportunity cost,

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:23.520
[Amit Varma]: for me to do a TV show out of this would actually take a lot of coordination and a lot of money,

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:27.680
[Amit Varma]: because who's going to do it? Where do you put together the thing? How do I look on camera?

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:33.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, I tell people I have a classic podcaster's face. So, but on the other hand,

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:38.160
[Amit Varma]: after the first few episodes, where you'll see that I'm a little self conscious, and I'm trying

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:42.800
[Amit Varma]: all kinds of things. After that one sort of settles down into a groove and you start having

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:48.960
[Amit Varma]: great conversations and sort of learning from it. So it was kind of accidental and like like

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:52.640
[Amit Varma]: most things in life, you know, most things in life aren't things you decide to do, they just

00:10:52.640 --> 00:11:01.280
[Unknown]: happen. Yes, absolutely. So Amit, so you've kept your podcast very India focused, you know,

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:05.680
[Unknown]: issues that plague the Indian people. I mean, I deeply appreciate it. And I really want to

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:11.360
[Unknown]: listen to a podcast on those. But so if you want to cover any political scenarios or any policy

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:16.160
[Unknown]: making issues on a global scale in different countries, you know, what topics would you

00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:21.680
[Amit Varma]: have liked covered? Yeah, I'm actually I've always intended not to keep it to India,

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:26.320
[Amit Varma]: but every few episodes do something with an international guest. And the thing is,

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:31.440
[Amit Varma]: I simply have been lazy about reaching out to them and doing it right. So Alex Tabarrok was here in

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:36.240
[Amit Varma]: Bombay for a while. Okay, so we met up and I got him here and I did a couple of episodes with him.

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:40.800
[Amit Varma]: So there are tons of people I want to reach out to, and kind of beg them to be a guest on my

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:48.480
[Amit Varma]: podcast. But I haven't really gotten down to it. I'd love to, for example, if you ask me who are

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:54.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of dream guests and dream subjects, I'd love to talk to Sam Harris about free will. Okay, I

00:11:54.880 --> 00:12:00.880
[Amit Varma]: don't believe in free will either. I think my, but I have certain nuances in the way I look at it.

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:04.400
[Amit Varma]: So that would be an interesting... That's the libertarian in you picking out.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:14.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so and a bunch of economists, I mean, just speak about, like, every time I read a fascinating

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:17.920
[Amit Varma]: book, I think, hey, I should speak to this person. Like, I keep thinking I should write to Philip

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:22.080
[Amit Varma]: Tetlock and, you know, ask him to be on the show because I loved his book, Super Forecasting. I

00:12:22.080 --> 00:12:24.960
[Amit Varma]: thought that's one of the best books I read in recent times. And a lot of the conclusions of

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:30.400
[Amit Varma]: that book also tied in very nicely with things that I learned in my years as a professional

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:36.320
[Amit Varma]: poker player, which I was. And that was very fascinating. But I've just been bloody lazy. And,

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:40.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, so at some point, I'll get over that. But I think like you said, I think one of the

00:12:40.720 --> 00:12:44.640
[Amit Varma]: reasons people listen to this is that if you're listening to international podcasts, there are

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:48.800
[Amit Varma]: like thousands of them, but Indian there are very few. Yes, absolutely. So, you know, keep the main

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:52.800
[Amit Varma]: focus Indian. But once in a while, if I do an international one, I'd love to if anyone agrees

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:56.800
[Unknown]: to come on the show. Nice. And I guess it's great that you played poker, because we got to listen

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:02.240
[Unknown]: to the episode, which is quite fantastic. Thanks. Yeah, coming from a financial services background.

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:05.920
[Unknown]: Right. Yeah. A lot of people I recommended the episode to also quite like that.

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:10.400
[Amit Varma]: Well, thanks so much. I mean, all credit to my guest, Mohit Satyanand, who is a man of immense

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:15.360
[Unknown]: wisdom. Yeah. As a listener, as someone who maybe started listening to this podcast for the first

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:20.800
[Unknown]: time and is now, you know, now his eyes are opened to new ideas that, hey, these are the unseen

00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:27.440
[Unknown]: effects of so-and-so policy or so-and-so decisions. So as a listener to these things, so how can I,

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:31.680
[Unknown]: how can a layman contribute, you know, to the political system or to policymaking in any way,

00:13:31.680 --> 00:13:35.200
[Unknown]: just as a singer, other than, of course, voting for the right people? What other things do you

00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:40.560
[Unknown]: think any, any person who's interested in this can do to effect change other than maybe start

00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:46.320
[Amit Varma]: his own podcast? Yeah, I mean, I think the key thing here is that it's not just about specific

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:50.400
[Amit Varma]: policies, like, yeh policy achha hai, yeh policy bura hai. It's more about a framework of looking

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:54.640
[Amit Varma]: at the world and about certain values that are within those framework, like, you know,

00:13:54.640 --> 00:13:58.320
[Amit Varma]: individual freedom is a good thing. We need to protect individual rights and so on and so forth.

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And my great lament is that those ideas are not in the culture, that a few English speaking

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:07.440
[Amit Varma]: elites like myself, and because you're listening to the show, like yourself may agree with them or

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:11.360
[Amit Varma]: engage with them, but they're absolutely not out in the culture. So in the culture,

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:16.000
[Amit Varma]: for example, there is widespread support for the notion that free speech should be restricted.

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:18.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, there's widespread support for the notion that

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:26.640
[Amit Varma]: you should not offend anybody and, and various other things which we would disagree with. Yes.

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:33.440
[Amit Varma]: So what I keep, you know, a lot of people who think about policy, look at it as a political

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:38.960
[Amit Varma]: battle, that okay, we are doing policy advocacy, and we have to convince politicians and bureaucrats

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:43.680
[Amit Varma]: and so on to change their policies and whatever. And I've always and I've come to the conclusion,

00:14:43.680 --> 00:14:48.480
[Amit Varma]: I didn't always believe like this, but I keep, I've sort of come to the conclusion that this is

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:53.680
[Amit Varma]: not about change is not going to happen politically. Change first has to happen culturally.

00:14:53.680 --> 00:14:58.400
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, one big reason of the great success of the alt-right in the US

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:01.440
[Amit Varma]: was their recognition of this, like Andrew Breitbart, who founded Breitbart,

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:07.360
[Amit Varma]: and who died a few years ago, he once said, and this is something I don't stop quoting,

00:15:07.360 --> 00:15:15.040
[Amit Varma]: that politics is downstream of culture. Okay. And, and, and what that indicates is that if you want

00:15:15.040 --> 00:15:20.880
[Amit Varma]: to change politics, you have to change culture. And none of us can personally really do much

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:26.240
[Amit Varma]: about changing politics. All of us can contribute to changing culture in our own really little ways.

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:30.160
[Amit Varma]: But to be frank, we are just individuals. And it seems futile. And what do you do when your

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:40.480
[Amit Varma]: family WhatsApp group with 10 uncles telling you Modiji is great. But, yeah, so I mean, yeah,

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:48.800
[Unknown]: that's, that's coming to coming, you know, taking off from Modiji is great. You spoke about this

00:15:48.800 --> 00:15:55.440
[Unknown]: entire mindset of the Indian voter to not let his vote go to waste. Right. And, but your view was

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:59.600
[Unknown]: that, you know, you should rather vote for the individual who's there in your constituency,

00:15:59.600 --> 00:16:04.240
[Unknown]: correct me if I'm wrong there, and not look at, you know, my vote is going to waste because

00:16:05.120 --> 00:16:09.760
[Unknown]: I should vote for Modiji because the world is doing so, or India is doing so. And hence I should

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:16.160
[Unknown]: vote for the BJP, you know, MLA or MP from my area. Right. So how do you really come into,

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:20.320
[Unknown]: you know, affecting that cultural change? So what do you change on ground to make that happen?

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:26.480
[Unknown]: Because to make people vote more, to make people vote more, no, but to make people vote or think

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:32.080
[Unknown]: about, you know, not thinking about the larger picture first, but starting from bottom up and

00:16:32.080 --> 00:16:37.200
[Amit Varma]: me voting for my guy first. Yeah. So it's, it's, it's complicated. And there are a number of

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:42.560
[Amit Varma]: questions within that question you asked. Uh, the first aspect that you look at is that local

00:16:42.560 --> 00:16:46.800
[Amit Varma]: government in India is not very strong. Now, ideally, what should happen is that power should

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:52.240
[Amit Varma]: be devolved from the centre to the state, to the city, to the ward and all that. So local government

00:16:52.240 --> 00:16:56.240
[Amit Varma]: actually matters. If somebody isn't collecting garbage outside your thing, your vote can make

00:16:56.240 --> 00:17:00.080
[Amit Varma]: a difference. Now, actually, your vote can't make a difference. And we had a I had a very

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:04.640
[Amit Varma]: interesting episode of the scene in the unseen on this with Shruti Rajgopalan on urban governance.

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And the key point she made there, which is something a lot of people don't realise about

00:17:10.320 --> 00:17:15.520
[Amit Varma]: the cities, or they do, which is why the apathetic is that there is a disconnect between power and

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:22.480
[Amit Varma]: accountability at the local government level. So what happens is that you have as a, you know,

00:17:22.480 --> 00:17:26.880
[Amit Varma]: who is accountable to you, your corporators and all are accountable to you, they need your vote,

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:30.320
[Amit Varma]: but do they have the power, they don't really have any power to do anything, they don't really

00:17:30.320 --> 00:17:37.040
[Amit Varma]: take any big decisions, flyover, they don't, who has the power, the state legislature has a power,

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:40.960
[Amit Varma]: because it's not devolved further. So the real power is with the state legislature.

00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:45.120
[Amit Varma]: And they're not accountable to you. They're not accountable to urban voters. If you think about

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:52.000
[Amit Varma]: it in practice, in the Maharashtra government, they're all the vote banks are rural vote banks,

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:58.560
[Amit Varma]: Mumbai per se doesn't really make a difference to that. So they can afford to ignore the urban vote

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:06.880
[Amit Varma]: and just pander to whatever different rural vote banks they might want to pander to. And which is

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:11.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, a government job is at the end of the day to all its people. So I'm not saying that you

00:18:11.200 --> 00:18:16.160
[Amit Varma]: should give a special, special privileges to urban voters, just because you've got more taxes coming

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:20.800
[Amit Varma]: out of Mumbai. That's not my point at all. My point is that government should be so localized,

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:26.400
[Amit Varma]: that there are that people who have power over you should be accountable to you. And in practice,

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:30.640
[Amit Varma]: that's not really the case. And I think that's the reason why people become so apathetic,

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:35.280
[Amit Varma]: because they realize that look, you know, fine, we're a democracy, but I can't really hold anybody

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:40.720
[Amit Varma]: accountable. Right? Because especially at a local government level. The other facet of this is the

00:18:40.720 --> 00:18:46.880
[Amit Varma]: fact that every voter knows, you know, you might tell people it's your duty to vote and so on. But

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:52.000
[Amit Varma]: every voter knows that his one vote is not going to decide an election. Right? Yeah. Right. There's

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:55.840
[Amit Varma]: a funny story about this, by the way, in some local election somewhere in the north, some guy

00:18:55.840 --> 00:19:02.640
[Amit Varma]: actually said this that he lost by one vote and his wife hadn't gone and voted. So I can't imagine

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:07.520
[Amit Varma]: that their family dinners were much fun after that. But yeah, so I think most people have the

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:12.880
[Amit Varma]: added have the attitude that what difference is my vote going to make? The system is rigged. And

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:17.520
[Amit Varma]: also one of the questions which comes up in the in the Ask Me Anything section, which Abbas will

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:21.280
[Amit Varma]: take us through at the end, and I'll repeat the question then and name the person to give you

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:29.440
[Amit Varma]: credit. But I think one of the questions was, look at all my options. Why should I vote? Look

00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:35.360
[Amit Varma]: at all you know, and there are two ways of looking at it. One way of looking at it is that you vote

00:19:35.360 --> 00:19:40.320
[Amit Varma]: for the person who is the least bad. So a lot of people today will say that, okay, look what

00:19:40.320 --> 00:19:44.640
[Amit Varma]: Modiji is doing to the country, which is absolutely true. And therefore you vote for whatever you

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:50.080
[Amit Varma]: think is the most viable alternative. Right? So that is one way of looking at it. And I'm leaning

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:55.680
[Amit Varma]: towards that. But my way of looking at it, which is slightly different is that I won't vote. And

00:19:55.680 --> 00:20:00.240
[Amit Varma]: here's the reason why. I won't vote because if you look at the political marketplace as a

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:06.800
[Amit Varma]: marketplace, now think of I go to a mall to buy a shirt. Okay. They're all crappy shirts. I buy the

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:12.320
[Unknown]: least crappy shirt. Right? Right. Yeah, I've got a crappy shirt. But if I don't buy a shirt, what

00:20:12.320 --> 00:20:17.440
[Amit Varma]: does that do? Because those sales aren't happening, that sends a signal to the marketplace that there

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:22.480
[Amit Varma]: is a market for shirts. And somebody some entrepreneur, the other will then make different

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:27.200
[Amit Varma]: shirts, which I might like. So similarly, in the political marketplace, it's a marketplace voting

00:20:27.200 --> 00:20:32.480
[Amit Varma]: is, it's a privilege, but it's not a duty. If you don't like any of the products, by not voting,

00:20:32.480 --> 00:20:37.040
[Amit Varma]: you send a message to political entrepreneurs, that X percent of the people haven't voted.

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:43.040
[Amit Varma]: And and therefore there is a market there. And I actually know people who go thinking like this

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:47.280
[Amit Varma]: right now and are working on it. And I'm sure this was part of the reason why, for example,

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Kejriwal and gang, I'm not a big fan of the man, but a talented political entrepreneur, and he came

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:57.360
[Amit Varma]: up and he won power because he obviously saw that apathy, where does that apathy reflect itself in

00:20:57.360 --> 00:21:02.080
[Amit Varma]: the percentage of people who are not voting. So even by not voting, you're sending a signal to

00:21:02.080 --> 00:21:07.440
[Amit Varma]: the marketplace, which might be important. Now, I'm very conflicted, because many close friends

00:21:07.440 --> 00:21:11.920
[Amit Varma]: of mine have been trying to convince me that no, you're wrong, that you think you're sending a

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:15.920
[Amit Varma]: signal to the marketplace, but there may be no marketplace, we are going towards despotism,

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:19.680
[Amit Varma]: and we need to do something now, and it's an emergency, and so on and so forth.

00:21:20.960 --> 00:21:24.400
[Amit Varma]: So to be honest, I'm conflicted between these two points of view, that should you vote for

00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:27.120
[Amit Varma]: whatever is the least bad option, or should you not vote at all?

00:21:27.120 --> 00:21:31.440
[Unknown]: And just a simple counter to, I was just thinking out loud, that you said, you know, you will,

00:21:31.440 --> 00:21:37.200
[Unknown]: you will express your sort of dissatisfaction by not voting. But say, how is any politician or

00:21:37.200 --> 00:21:41.440
[Unknown]: anybody actually able to differentiate that suppose 30% people have not voted in the next election?

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:46.960
[Unknown]: So how can you say that this 30 people have not have chosen to not vote or have just sat in their

00:21:46.960 --> 00:21:50.800
[Unknown]: homes and said, this country is not going to win. So yeah, those are two very different things,

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:55.120
[Unknown]: right? Right, right. I'm busy and I'm not not voting, for example, and you're sitting in your

00:21:55.120 --> 00:21:58.880
[Unknown]: home and saying, I'm not going to vote. Like, it's a choice.

00:21:58.880 --> 00:22:05.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but but it, no, I, I think in terms of actions, I think it's actually the same thing.

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:10.880
[Amit Varma]: It's it's whether I vote from this conscious sort of rational process that I have, whether I

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:15.200
[Amit Varma]: refrain from voting for that reason, or whether I just don't give a shit about politics. And I'm

00:22:15.200 --> 00:22:20.880
[Amit Varma]: doing my thing. It's actually the same thing, it indicates that you don't care for the options out

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:27.680
[Amit Varma]: there. And therefore, there is an opening that you might, you know, care for that somebody might want

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:31.600
[Amit Varma]: to provide an option. And you know, if you eventually have those kinds of figures, and I've

00:22:31.600 --> 00:22:36.480
[Amit Varma]: actually sat with a political entrepreneur who is thinking or was thinking of launching his own

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:42.000
[Amit Varma]: party. And he went through constituency wise figures of how many people haven't voted in

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:47.280
[Amit Varma]: each district and broke it down and spoke about where he thinks his niche might be and whatever.

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:51.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's just one person I have access to. I'm sure across the country there are

00:22:52.080 --> 00:22:56.480
[Amit Varma]: and this is a common lament all of us have, ki vote karo to kisk ke liye vote karo.

00:22:56.480 --> 00:23:00.480
[Amit Varma]: Surely some entrepreneur is going to come out of somewhere and try to capitalize on that, right?

00:23:00.480 --> 00:23:02.320
[Amit Varma]: Keshival did, for example.

00:23:02.320 --> 00:23:05.280
[Unknown]: I think I think this topic deserves a podcast episode of its own.

00:23:05.280 --> 00:23:07.520
[Amit Varma]: A full podcast. Do you have any guests you'd recommend?

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:09.440
[Amit Varma]: I'm serious.

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:09.920
[Unknown]: Not really.

00:23:11.360 --> 00:23:14.960
[Unknown]: So this also partly answers another, I was just going through the AMA

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:18.960
[Unknown]: post on Twitter. And someone's just asked about, you know, what are the advantages,

00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:20.960
[Unknown]: disadvantages, etc. of having a nota.

00:23:20.960 --> 00:23:25.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, see, I think that the nota is like, if you really have,

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:28.800
[Amit Varma]: like your time is no opportunity cost, you've got fucking nothing to do,

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:32.800
[Amit Varma]: then you go and vote nota. Because to me, a non vote and a vote for nota is the same thing.

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:35.840
[Unknown]: To me, by the logic I just gave now.

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:39.600
[Amit Varma]: So what's the point of voting nota? Why go all the way there and,

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:43.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, just, just vote nota. Either you vote for someone or you don't vote at all,

00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:46.560
[Amit Varma]: which is sending the same message for less effort, you know?

00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:49.120
[Unknown]: But isn't that a stronger signal then?

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:54.000
[Unknown]: Okay, fine, people are coming out and saying nota rather than just as Nakul was just pointing out.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.120
[Unknown]: And I have a that, you know, you might just be laid back, relaxed and not

00:23:57.120 --> 00:24:01.200
[Unknown]: give too much too many fucks about, you know, going there because I'm happy.

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:04.480
[Unknown]: I don't care who's there at the, at the center right now.

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:05.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm indifferent.

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:08.880
[Amit Varma]: I think that would be true if the nota percentage could be significant.

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:13.200
[Amit Varma]: Like one of my friends campaigned for nota in the recent Mumbai municipal elections.

00:24:13.200 --> 00:24:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And I think he spent a lot of money doing it.

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:17.280
[Amit Varma]: Though I used to keep telling him that, you know,

00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:19.360
[Amit Varma]: you should have a fricking product for a political campaign.

00:24:19.360 --> 00:24:21.040
[Amit Varma]: Why are you campaigning for fricking nota?

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:23.040
[Amit Varma]: I think he got the percent off from one to two.

00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:23.760
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:24:23.760 --> 00:24:26.720
[Amit Varma]: Right. And your non voters would be, you know, in the tens.

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:32.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So, you know, unless you, unless you get, if 30% of the people vote nota, I agree with you.

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:39.120
[Amit Varma]: Everybody would stand up and say, okay, my God, you know, but one or two percent, no one really care.

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:46.160
[Unknown]: A broader question, which I have is that right now we're as a country.

00:24:46.160 --> 00:24:51.760
[Unknown]: And in fact, across the globe, we're more divided than ever in the sense that there's either,

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:55.440
[Unknown]: I mean, you are, you're right, you're on the, you're far right or I'm far left.

00:24:55.440 --> 00:25:01.360
[Unknown]: And I mean, you have your magazines, your, your political thinkers and your ideas.

00:25:01.360 --> 00:25:06.240
[Unknown]: And I have my own, if I'm a left guy, I have my own New York Times and my Trevor Noah's of the world.

00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:11.440
[Unknown]: And so how do, is there any way that we can bridge that gap today?

00:25:11.440 --> 00:25:15.680
[Unknown]: Like that, is that possible for people to meet somewhere halfway down?

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:21.520
[Unknown]: Because earlier we, I mean, things were not so divided that people didn't have their own.

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:24.800
[Unknown]: I mean, you're, you don't live in your own bubble at least some time back,

00:25:24.800 --> 00:25:27.040
[Unknown]: but now we've become very divided.

00:25:27.040 --> 00:25:29.200
[Unknown]: I'm sure in the future, it's just going to increase more.

00:25:29.200 --> 00:25:30.800
[Unknown]: The contrast is going to be even sharper.

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:33.760
[Unknown]: So is there any way that this can be sort of healed?

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:34.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's a good question.

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:37.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, and the reason this has happened interestingly is technology.

00:25:37.440 --> 00:25:39.360
[Amit Varma]: We used to think technology will bring the world together,

00:25:39.360 --> 00:25:43.520
[Amit Varma]: but technology actually makes it easier to form echo chambers and

00:25:44.720 --> 00:25:46.800
[Amit Varma]: live in the comfort of your own worldview.

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:49.120
[Amit Varma]: And you might be the most bigoted racist person out there,

00:25:49.120 --> 00:25:53.840
[Amit Varma]: but technology enables you to discover millions of other bigoted racist people like you.

00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:57.600
[Unknown]: And then you take comfort in numbers and you're no longer the odd one out in your family.

00:25:59.280 --> 00:26:02.560
[Amit Varma]: Though overall, I think technology is a huge net positive.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:04.320
[Amit Varma]: But yes, this has happened.

00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:06.320
[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

00:26:06.320 --> 00:26:10.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one glib answer, so glib I feel embarrassed to give it is maybe culture,

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:14.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, we can still like the same movies and the same music or whatever.

00:26:14.240 --> 00:26:14.720
[Unknown]: I don't know.

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:18.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's very hard.

00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:24.160
[Amit Varma]: And the question that I'd written an op-ed in The Hindu about this, I think, late last year,

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:25.120
[Unknown]: December.

00:26:25.120 --> 00:26:30.160
[Amit Varma]: And the question that I'm asking, which I can't find an answer for is

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:32.560
[Amit Varma]: people keep talking about fake news.

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:34.160
[Amit Varma]: How do you break through it?

00:26:34.160 --> 00:26:34.720
[Amit Varma]: How?

00:26:34.720 --> 00:26:37.920
[Amit Varma]: Because earlier, what would happen is that even if a rumor spreads,

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:40.640
[Amit Varma]: you have these authoritative sources of information.

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:41.520
[Unknown]: Everybody trusts.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:42.000
[Unknown]: Absolutely.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.880
[Amit Varma]: You have your New York Times or your Times of India or whoever.

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:46.480
[Amit Varma]: But now that is all diffused.

00:26:46.480 --> 00:26:47.040
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

00:26:47.040 --> 00:26:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Now everybody has their sources of, you know, WhatsApp baba ki jai.

00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:53.440
[Amit Varma]: And people have adopted a worldview.

00:26:53.440 --> 00:26:54.960
[Amit Varma]: They will, it's confirmation bias.

00:26:54.960 --> 00:26:59.520
[Amit Varma]: They will only take whatever fits into their worldview and reject everything else.

00:26:59.520 --> 00:27:00.560
[Amit Varma]: How do you break through this?

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:01.600
[Amit Varma]: I don't have an answer.

00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:02.560
[Amit Varma]: It's so, how?

00:27:02.560 --> 00:27:02.880
[Unknown]: Tell me.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:09.280
[Unknown]: That comes back to the latest episode where the debate is all about, you know, should you regulate

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:11.840
[Amit Varma]: the likes of Facebook, Google, etc.

00:27:11.840 --> 00:27:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:13.600
[Amit Varma]: Which I, which I think is the wrong answer.

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:17.920
[Amit Varma]: You give government the power, you're going to get screwed because whenever you give any

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:23.920
[Amit Varma]: power to government, you must assume, you must imagine the worst possible person being

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:25.200
[Unknown]: in that government.

00:27:25.200 --> 00:27:29.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, so if you're a left liberal, you should imagine Adityanath in that government.

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:34.880
[Amit Varma]: If you are a hardcore Hindu person, you should imagine Sonia Gandhi or whoever, whoever's

00:27:34.880 --> 00:27:41.280
[Amit Varma]: your nightmare, Sitaram Yachuri in the government, you know, using that too, because ultimately

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:44.560
[Amit Varma]: any power that you give to government, government never lets go of it.

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:48.960
[Amit Varma]: And the more power you give government, the more oppression becomes inevitable.

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:53.600
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's an easy answer that people are searching for, because in India, there

00:27:53.600 --> 00:27:57.600
[Amit Varma]: is also this tendency for everything to say that the government should do something about

00:27:57.600 --> 00:27:57.760
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:27:57.760 --> 00:27:58.560
[Amit Varma]: Yes, absolutely.

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:04.880
[Amit Varma]: And I think the unseen effects of that are just something no one thinks about.

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:08.400
[Amit Varma]: And concentrating too much power in the hand of government is...

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:11.440
[Unknown]: I mean, in the 70s, I mean, the government used to make watches, right?

00:28:11.440 --> 00:28:11.920
[Unknown]: In the 70s.

00:28:11.920 --> 00:28:14.560
[Unknown]: And now when I think back, I mean, why is the government making watches?

00:28:14.560 --> 00:28:15.920
[Unknown]: Why was the government making watches?

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:16.160
[Amit Varma]: Like...

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:17.520
[Amit Varma]: The government makes sex toys.

