00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:47.520
[Amit Varma]: which, you know, people on the left will go for, though I would argue that freedom is

00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:51.280
[Amit Varma]: gives you the best shot at equality, but equality of opportunity.

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:54.320
[Amit Varma]: But that could be another framework, you have a third framework could be the,

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:56.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, the whole conservative framework where you say that

00:35:56.960 --> 00:35:59.760
[Amit Varma]: things have worked a certain way given human nature for a while,

00:35:59.760 --> 00:36:01.280
[Amit Varma]: and we should not mess with it too much.

00:36:01.280 --> 00:36:02.000
[Unknown]: Right.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.080
[Amit Varma]: And so on and so forth.

00:36:04.080 --> 00:36:09.040
[Amit Varma]: I think one of the things that any whichever way you look at the world

00:36:09.040 --> 00:36:11.280
[Amit Varma]: has to take into account is human nature itself.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.760
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is that there is a duality to humans.

00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:19.680
[Amit Varma]: There is one part of us, which is basically animals,

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:22.960
[Amit Varma]: that our brains are hardwired in certain ways, in the sense that

00:36:22.960 --> 00:36:26.400
[Amit Varma]: our tribalism is hardwired into us, our bigotry is hardwired into us,

00:36:26.400 --> 00:36:28.640
[Amit Varma]: our misogyny is hardwired into us.

00:36:28.640 --> 00:36:33.680
[Amit Varma]: And all of all of those hardwirings find a reflection in culture and the way,

00:36:33.680 --> 00:36:37.040
[Amit Varma]: for example, the way the patriarchy is set up, the way the power systems work,

00:36:37.040 --> 00:36:42.960
[Amit Varma]: and the other instinctive distrust of the other throughout the world.

00:36:42.960 --> 00:36:43.440
[Amit Varma]: Of course.

00:36:43.440 --> 00:36:46.800
[Amit Varma]: And so that is really a reflection of the dark side of human nature.

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:51.040
[Amit Varma]: But what humans also have the other side is that we have also been,

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:55.040
[Amit Varma]: I won't say blessed, because it makes it seem like I believe in God,

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:58.480
[Amit Varma]: but we are also lucky enough, much better word for me,

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:03.040
[Amit Varma]: we're also lucky enough to possess brains, which can actually self reflect,

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:04.800
[Amit Varma]: and which can think about all this,

00:37:04.800 --> 00:37:09.120
[Amit Varma]: and which can understand that this is a programming and we need to go beyond that.

00:37:09.120 --> 00:37:13.280
[Amit Varma]: And to me, what we've seen culturally in the last three centuries,

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:17.920
[Amit Varma]: since the Enlightenment is essentially that is earlier culture

00:37:17.920 --> 00:37:20.480
[Amit Varma]: was something that reinforced human nature.

00:37:20.480 --> 00:37:24.960
[Amit Varma]: And in the last three, 400 years, culture has begun to mitigate human nature

00:37:24.960 --> 00:37:28.640
[Amit Varma]: and to fight against it. And to fight against those instincts,

00:37:28.640 --> 00:37:32.560
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, whether it's a simple thing like me deciding not to have a child,

00:37:32.560 --> 00:37:39.280
[Amit Varma]: where I'm fighting my hardwiring, right, or whether it's a various ways,

00:37:39.280 --> 00:37:42.000
[Amit Varma]: equality for women, for example, comes out of culture.

00:37:43.360 --> 00:37:48.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, as time goes, we've become like there is the philosopher W.E.H. Leckie,

00:37:48.080 --> 00:37:51.600
[Amit Varma]: 19th century philosopher, he'd come up with this phrase called the expanding circle.

00:37:51.600 --> 00:38:00.400
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so his what he postulated was that all of us that since prehistoric times,

00:38:00.400 --> 00:38:03.360
[Amit Varma]: there has been an expanding circle around humanity. What does that mean?

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:07.040
[Amit Varma]: That means that if you go back to our prehistoric ancestor,

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:09.760
[Amit Varma]: there are a circle of people that is his family or his tribe,

00:38:09.760 --> 00:38:12.400
[Amit Varma]: who he deems worthy of moral consideration.

00:38:12.400 --> 00:38:15.360
[Amit Varma]: Nobody outside that tribe is worthy of that moral consideration.

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:17.680
[Amit Varma]: So if he's at war with them, he will kill them, he will rape them,

00:38:17.680 --> 00:38:20.080
[Amit Varma]: he will do whatever they're not human beings at all.

00:38:20.080 --> 00:38:24.880
[Amit Varma]: Now, Leckie's postulation was that this circle has expanded through human history.

00:38:24.880 --> 00:38:30.800
[Amit Varma]: It's expanded from the family to the tribe, to maybe alliances of tribes, to a nation,

00:38:30.800 --> 00:38:36.240
[Amit Varma]: to an ethnicity, and it's kept expanding till all of humanity is in it for some people.

00:38:36.240 --> 00:38:39.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, different people have different circles of people they consider worthy of the moral

00:38:39.840 --> 00:38:47.440
[Amit Varma]: consideration. And the utilitarian philosopher Peter Singer, in fact, wrote a book about this

00:38:47.440 --> 00:38:50.480
[Amit Varma]: called The Expanding Circle, where he argued that it should expand to include animals.

00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:55.840
[Amit Varma]: Right now, that's a different argument in itself. And let's not go there.

00:38:55.840 --> 00:39:01.200
[Amit Varma]: But it's worth thinking of. I mean, it's possible that the way we today look down on,

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:05.760
[Amit Varma]: say, Thomas Jefferson for having slaves, future generations may look down on us for killing

00:39:05.760 --> 00:39:09.120
[Amit Varma]: animals. And of course, by that time, you won't have to kill animals to eat meat,

00:39:09.120 --> 00:39:13.440
[Amit Varma]: you'll grow it in labs. That's almost around the corner.

00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:18.400
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, so there's that thing of the expanding circle. Now, the thing is that

00:39:19.600 --> 00:39:25.600
[Amit Varma]: overall, yeah, people circles have vastly expanded. And you see this more in the big cities

00:39:25.600 --> 00:39:30.160
[Amit Varma]: than in small areas, because cities tend to be cosmopolitan. And it's also in your economic

00:39:30.160 --> 00:39:34.880
[Amit Varma]: interest to have the largest networks to be part of the largest networks you can be and so on.

00:39:34.880 --> 00:39:38.960
[Amit Varma]: But they haven't expanded enough. And you see that even in India, like one of the really

00:39:38.960 --> 00:39:44.080
[Amit Varma]: disturbing questions that came up in the last few weeks was during the Asifa case, that how

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:50.160
[Amit Varma]: could someone do this to any? How could you to another human being? Where is your humanity?

00:39:50.160 --> 00:39:53.600
[Amit Varma]: But the answer to this is that the people who did this did not consider

00:39:54.560 --> 00:40:01.440
[Amit Varma]: her worthy of their moral consideration. She was from the Bakarwal tribe, Muslim tribe,

00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:07.520
[Amit Varma]: and those people weren't part of the circle of these people who, you know, their circle hadn't

