[Unknown]: think he used to be a cricket writer. I see. Yeah. So his question is, why do you think urban

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:13.200
[Unknown]: Indians are so disconnected from reality? Ask a random sample of urban Indians in any decent

00:45:13.200 --> 00:45:17.680
[Unknown]: sized city. Only a minority would know what they're drinking. Only a minority would know

00:45:17.680 --> 00:45:22.400
[Unknown]: what their drinking water sources are, where their food comes from. It's the biggest reason they vote

00:45:22.400 --> 00:45:27.600
[Amit Varma]: wrong come election time. Two sides of this. I'll give the positive side first. The positive side is

00:45:27.600 --> 00:45:33.600
[Amit Varma]: there's this famous essay called I pencil by Leonard Reed and famous essay, just Google it.

00:45:33.600 --> 00:45:39.840
[Amit Varma]: I pencil by Leonard Reed. And what that essay is about is the autobiography of a pencil, which

00:45:39.840 --> 00:45:45.760
[Amit Varma]: talks about how it's made. And what you realize through that is that it can't be made by any one

00:45:45.760 --> 00:45:53.280
[Amit Varma]: person. It takes literally it has raw material from across the world, made by 1000s of people

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:59.520
[Amit Varma]: requiring you know, the cooperation and coordination of millions to actually produce that one pencil

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:04.320
[Amit Varma]: and yet none of these people know of any of the others. I think a recent version of this was done

00:46:04.320 --> 00:46:11.040
[Amit Varma]: as a homage to this, which was about the iPod, about how the iPod is made with inputs from 70

00:46:11.040 --> 00:46:14.560
[Amit Varma]: countries or whatever. And all these people don't know all the other people. So this lack of

00:46:14.560 --> 00:46:20.400
[Amit Varma]: knowledge is not necessarily a bug. It's actually a feature, it means that you can go about your

00:46:20.400 --> 00:46:26.240
[Amit Varma]: daily life. And without your knowing it or planning for it. There are millions of people across the

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:32.400
[Amit Varma]: world who are working at this moment to satisfy your needs. That's the wonder of a market. But

00:46:32.400 --> 00:46:38.800
[Amit Varma]: that's obviously not Krishnakumar at later cut is referring to what he's referring to is why are we

00:46:38.800 --> 00:46:43.280
[Amit Varma]: so apathetic? And again, that is something we discussed earlier, Ajit had asked a question

00:46:43.280 --> 00:46:48.480
[Amit Varma]: about that. And the thing is, our apathy is rational, because it is indeed true that we

00:46:48.480 --> 00:46:52.640
[Amit Varma]: can do nothing about it, not just because rationally, one vote makes no difference,

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:57.040
[Amit Varma]: but also because there is a disconnect between power and accountability at the level of local

00:46:57.040 --> 00:47:04.080
[Amit Varma]: government. And the forces that are around us sometimes seem too overwhelming to do anything

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:10.560
[Amit Varma]: about. And if I've interpreted his lament correctly, it's a lament I share, I don't have

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:14.720
[Unknown]: any solutions. I mean, what do you do? You just go on doing what you're doing. Okay. He's tried

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:22.080
[Unknown]: to connect the apathy to voting wrongly in the elections. Yeah, I mean, voting wrongly. It's

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:29.520
[Amit Varma]: what is wrongly, it's not like there's a right option, right? Everybody is entitled to everybody

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:33.200
[Amit Varma]: is entitled to their view of looking at the world. And also everybody is wrong. And

00:47:33.200 --> 00:47:42.240
[Unknown]: there's nothing more to say life is sad. All right. So Mr. Dodwani asked another question,

00:47:42.240 --> 00:47:46.960
[Unknown]: which I found pretty interesting, where he asks, most of India's problems lie in yesteryear's law

00:47:46.960 --> 00:47:52.320
[Unknown]: that don't work for modern society. Is there a way to rewrite the Constitution of India understanding

00:47:52.320 --> 00:47:57.280
[Unknown]: the needs of the present time and dealing with them more aptly? Yeah, but who's going to do it?

00:47:57.280 --> 00:48:02.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, if the Constitution is rewritten, it won't be by Mr. Dodwani or me. It'll be by the

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:10.640
[Amit Varma]: people in charge. They will make it worse. Right. So it's an easy thing to sort of say that, you

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:15.120
[Amit Varma]: know, see, it's first of all, it's true that the Constitution doesn't go far enough to protect our

00:48:15.120 --> 00:48:20.800
[Amit Varma]: freedoms. For example, free speech is not protected. Article 19 to lays out all those

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:27.280
[Amit Varma]: restrictions to it, such as public order, decency, and so on. And because of that, various laws in

00:48:27.280 --> 00:48:32.400
[Amit Varma]: the IPC, which were framed by the British to oppress us, like 295A, 153A, which make it a

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:36.560
[Amit Varma]: crime to give offense, though you breached those laws off on a bus in your stand-up comedy,

00:48:37.680 --> 00:48:42.080
[Amit Varma]: cannot be challenged constitutionally, because hey, the Constitution allows for laws like that.

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:46.720
[Amit Varma]: So our Constitution, people call it a liberal Constitution in the good sense of the word

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:53.520
[Amit Varma]: liberal. I don't think it is really, it doesn't protect our freedoms enough. And also, my good

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:59.440
[Amit Varma]: friend Shruti Rajgopalan, who's been on the show a few times, she had done an awesome presentation

00:48:59.440 --> 00:49:04.240
[Amit Varma]: somewhere on YouTube, if you search for her name, you'll find it about how the Constitution has been

00:49:04.240 --> 00:49:09.120
[Amit Varma]: consistently over the last 70 something years been amended time and time again, for political

00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:13.440
[Amit Varma]: purposes still is practically meaningless. So Ambedkar in 53, in fact, said that, you know,

00:49:13.440 --> 00:49:17.040
[Amit Varma]: the Constitution of India should be burnt because it is meaningless. Okay, very strong words. I

00:49:17.040 --> 00:49:21.040
[Amit Varma]: don't remember his exact words. Shruti's presentation, which will be on YouTube,

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:26.640
[Amit Varma]: Shruti Rajgopalan. And there was a cartoon at one point about how the Constitution of India is not a

00:49:26.640 --> 00:49:31.440
[Amit Varma]: book, but a periodical. It's changed so much. So politicians have been changing it throughout to

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:36.960
[Amit Varma]: their, so our Constitution is a pretty messed up beast. It's got some very good elements of it

00:49:36.960 --> 00:49:42.400
[Amit Varma]: still, it does offer us some protections, it could be far worse. And the worry is that if you wanted

00:49:42.400 --> 00:49:48.080
[Amit Varma]: to be amended, it could actually become far worse depending on the dispensation. Now, at some point,

00:49:48.080 --> 00:49:52.560
[Amit Varma]: I remember I got into this controversy on Twitter, because you can't make everything idiot proof,

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:58.320
[Amit Varma]: where right wingers were talking about changing the Constitution. Yeah. And somebody pointed out

00:49:58.320 --> 00:50:02.480
[Amit Varma]: that, oh, it can't be done. And I merely pointed out that, hey, it can be done. It's been done

00:50:02.480 --> 00:50:06.320
[Amit Varma]: repeatedly by Nehru and Indira. It's fucked us over. The right to property is no longer a

00:50:06.320 --> 00:50:11.600
[Amit Varma]: fundamental right. Right. And so without saying glibly, it can't be done, realized that it can

00:50:11.600 --> 00:50:15.760
[Amit Varma]: be done. And we should be aware and we should fight it. Okay. And that was because I wasn't

00:50:15.760 --> 00:50:20.560
[Amit Varma]: idiot proof enough. That was misinterpreted as my supporting a change to the Constitution.

00:50:20.560 --> 00:50:24.880
[Amit Varma]: But I would just say that, look, if someone's going to change it, it's not Mr. Dodwani or me,

00:50:24.880 --> 00:50:30.400
[Unknown]: it's Mr. Adityanath and Mr. Vinay Katiyar. So do you really want that? Yeah, that's the one

00:50:30.400 --> 00:50:34.640
[Unknown]: question that comes into my head. If we change laws to protect free speech, there are also someone

00:50:34.640 --> 00:50:39.760
[Unknown]: will stand up and say, try and change a lot to bring in Hindutva or Sharia law. So yeah, like

00:50:39.760 --> 00:50:46.960
[Unknown]: there'll always be that second point of view. Alright, Arvind Iyer on Twitter asks, I would

00:50:46.960 --> 00:50:51.920
[Unknown]: love to hear your views on US gun control with your consent and free trade principle. I think

00:50:51.920 --> 00:50:55.600
[Amit Varma]: you would oppose any restrictions. Can you share more details? Yeah, we should go to Twitter ID.

00:50:55.600 --> 00:51:01.360
[Amit Varma]: I think if I'm not mistaken, it's at Iyer Archie. That's right. Yeah, I don't know this person,

00:51:01.360 --> 00:51:05.600
[Amit Varma]: but I just remembered the ID because I was writing all these down. That's a great question. And I'm

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:11.600
[Amit Varma]: afraid I must disagree with my libertarian friends. I am for gun control. I don't believe guns should

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:18.080
[Amit Varma]: be freely sold in India. Now to explain why. Let me first say that in the US context, I imagine,

00:51:18.640 --> 00:51:24.080
[Amit Varma]: in the US context, I completely understand looking at how the country originated and how it has since

00:51:24.080 --> 00:51:27.600
[Amit Varma]: come by gun rights for a big deal, because you actually needed to protect yourself from the

00:51:27.600 --> 00:51:31.840
[Amit Varma]: state and so on and so forth. And that's how it originated. I understand that. I am, however,

00:51:31.840 --> 00:51:37.040
[Amit Varma]: glad that guns are not sold freely in India. And I hope they never are. And I wrote a post a long

00:51:37.040 --> 00:51:41.040
[Amit Varma]: time back called the Bomzuka question. That's the name of the post. If you just go on my blog,

00:51:41.040 --> 00:51:46.080
[Amit Varma]: IndiaUncut.com, search for Bomzuka, you'll come across a post where I pose a hypothetical

00:51:46.080 --> 00:51:50.880
[Amit Varma]: question. Let me post this to you guys as well. It's a difficult question. The question is this.

00:51:51.600 --> 00:51:57.680
[Amit Varma]: Imagine three kinds of weapons that are sold. Okay. One is a knife. You need a knife for cutting

00:51:57.680 --> 00:52:02.240
[Amit Varma]: vegetables and so on and so forth. You can also use it to kill people. Should a knife be allowed?

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:07.840
[Amit Varma]: Question one. Question two, gun. You can use a gun for self-defense. You can also kill people

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:14.400
[Amit Varma]: with it and it's got deterrence value. Should a gun be allowed? Weapon three, Bomzuka. Okay,

00:52:14.400 --> 00:52:18.800
[Amit Varma]: Bomzuka is my invention. That is my notional invention. I haven't actually invented something

00:52:18.800 --> 00:52:23.600
[Amit Varma]: like that. It's an invention. The Bomzuka is something which people are demandingly sold at

00:52:23.600 --> 00:52:27.600
[Amit Varma]: groceries. Everyone is allowed to buy. And what it basically does is you can press a button or

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:32.720
[Amit Varma]: remotely you can set it off and a whole neighborhood blows up. Let's say a few square hundred meters

00:52:32.720 --> 00:52:38.160
[Amit Varma]: just blow up. And there are people saying that, hey, you know, it's, you can't condemn me till

00:52:38.160 --> 00:52:44.160
[Amit Varma]: I've done it. And men kill, you know, guns don't, Bomzukas don't kill people. People kill people.

00:52:44.160 --> 00:52:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, should a Bomzuka be allowed? Now I think, so first knives, should it be allowed?

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:55.600
[Unknown]: I say yes. Yeah. So knife should be allowed to be sold, right? Because it has daily utility as well.

00:52:55.600 --> 00:53:00.720
[Unknown]: Right. Three Bomzukas, should it be allowed? Any random guy can buy a Bomzuka and blow up a

00:53:00.720 --> 00:53:06.320
[Amit Varma]: neighborhood? Not really. No. No. Right. Okay. So clear answers. Now, my only, my follow up

00:53:06.320 --> 00:53:10.560
[Amit Varma]: question then is, forget the second one about guns. My follow up question then is that somewhere

00:53:10.560 --> 00:53:17.120
[Amit Varma]: between the knife and a Bomzuka, you are drawing a line. Where is that line? And why is that line

00:53:17.120 --> 00:53:22.720
[Amit Varma]: there? You know, I think you'd both agree with me because you said knife should be sold and Bomzuka

00:53:22.720 --> 00:53:28.560
[Amit Varma]: should not be sold. That there should be a line. Where should that line be? And why there?

00:53:29.360 --> 00:53:35.520
[Unknown]: The line is in, I think, two parts. One is the magnitude of damage it can do. Maybe that's one.

00:53:36.080 --> 00:53:43.040
[Unknown]: And secondly, a knife also has a lot of other utilities. So two benevolent, less harmful

00:53:43.040 --> 00:53:49.120
[Amit Varma]: utilities. Exactly. And a Bomzuka doesn't. Right. So, which is a great answer, which is, which are

00:53:49.120 --> 00:53:53.680
[Amit Varma]: two of the parameters I'd look at. But I'd say that it is now very clear. And I think even the

00:53:53.680 --> 00:53:57.680
[Amit Varma]: most ardent libertarian would agree that you can't have Bomzukas selling over the counter where you

00:53:57.680 --> 00:54:01.040
[Amit Varma]: can just press a button and blow up a neighborhood because hey, we're f***ed, right? End of

00:54:01.040 --> 00:54:05.440
[Amit Varma]: civilization. So you are drawing a line. You're drawing a line. What are the reasons you're

00:54:05.440 --> 00:54:08.560
[Amit Varma]: drawing a line? And then you can debate about whether guns should be part of it or not.

00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:13.840
[Amit Varma]: I personally feel guns should be part of it. And how I justify that with my libertarian principles

00:54:13.840 --> 00:54:20.160
[Amit Varma]: is that part of what a libertarian recognizes as a valid role of state, the one valid role of state

00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:26.880
[Amit Varma]: is to protect all our rights. And this is sort of one preemptive way of doing that, of avoiding

00:54:26.880 --> 00:54:31.600
[Amit Varma]: violence. This justification can be misused. So I'm even hesitant of giving it out. And many of

00:54:31.600 --> 00:54:37.200
[Amit Varma]: my libertarian friends are very angry at me right now. And perhaps, you know, tearing the headphones

00:54:37.200 --> 00:54:42.400
[Amit Varma]: apart. I hope they're not expensive ones. But, but yeah, and look in India, man, come on, look

00:54:42.400 --> 00:54:50.560
[Amit Varma]: around you. Yeah, if you had guns selling freely, they would be freaking mayhem. I agree. Abbas,

00:54:50.560 --> 00:54:54.400
[Amit Varma]: do you agree with me? I do agree with you. Imagine, I mean, would you feel comfortable

00:54:54.400 --> 00:55:01.360
[Unknown]: as a stand up comedian? I have nightmares of a person standing up and aiming at the stage.

00:55:01.360 --> 00:55:06.800
[Unknown]: All right, we'll move on to the next question. So at Manish T on Twitter asks, if ever a private

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:12.880
[Unknown]: bank goes bankrupt, government will have to bail it out like the US in 2008. Then why not let

00:55:12.880 --> 00:55:18.400
[Unknown]: government participate in profits of the banks by owning them? Good question. And where I will

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:22.560
[Amit Varma]: take issue with the question is not the second sentence, but the first one, that private banks

00:55:22.560 --> 00:55:26.960
[Amit Varma]: should not be bailed out by the government that what happened in the financial crisis of 2007,

00:55:26.960 --> 00:55:30.560
[Amit Varma]: where the government bailed out all these private banks was wrong and create something called moral

00:55:30.560 --> 00:55:36.720
[Amit Varma]: hazard. It sets the wrong incentives, because all these companies then realize that they can do

00:55:36.720 --> 00:55:41.920
[Amit Varma]: whatever in the end, the government will bail them out. What does that do that privatizes profits,

00:55:41.920 --> 00:55:48.640
[Amit Varma]: it socializes losses. If the company makes money, they get the profits. If the company loses money,

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:53.200
[Amit Varma]: we the taxpayers pay. So I don't care what you say about the economy going down. I think that

00:55:53.200 --> 00:55:57.920
[Amit Varma]: was a rationalization that was alarmism. I think no private company should ever under any

00:55:57.920 --> 00:56:02.080
[Amit Varma]: circumstances be propped up by the government. It creates a moral hazard, which makes a second

00:56:02.080 --> 00:56:06.560
[Unknown]: part of the question and talking about just adding to that incentivizing them to perform better.

