00:58:39.680 --> 00:58:45.920
[Unknown]: All right, we'll go on to quickly to the next question is asked by at Shan say at Twitter.

00:58:45.920 --> 00:58:51.040
[Unknown]: His name is Shantanu. He asks, Will Indians create a liberal party like Swatantra in the future to

00:58:51.040 --> 00:58:55.920
[Unknown]: defeat socialist parties like BJP and Congress? Who do you think would be new Rajaji's and

00:58:55.920 --> 00:59:00.720
[Amit Varma]: Mussonni's emerging from? Great question. That's a question we've been asking ourselves for,

00:59:00.720 --> 00:59:04.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, almost decades, virtually, I make myself sound older than I am.

00:59:05.520 --> 00:59:11.840
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, a lot of people very foolishly put their faith in the BJP and thought that when Modi

00:59:11.840 --> 00:59:17.760
[Amit Varma]: said things like minimum government, maximum governance, that he was of that persuasion.

00:59:17.760 --> 00:59:20.480
[Amit Varma]: By the way, that line was on a cover of Pragati many, many years ago.

00:59:20.480 --> 00:59:28.640
[Unknown]: I mean, I wasn't part of it. So I have, but I mean, I wasn't part of Pragati,

00:59:28.640 --> 00:59:34.400
[Amit Varma]: then this is what I've been told. But, but like Shantanu correctly said in his question,

00:59:34.400 --> 00:59:41.120
[Amit Varma]: Modi is as socialist as all the as his favorite Nehru or Indira, if not more in some ways.

00:59:43.360 --> 00:59:48.320
[Amit Varma]: The point is, I'll go back to what I said earlier, when when I think of the political marketplace,

00:59:48.320 --> 00:59:52.560
[Amit Varma]: the party is part of the supply, right? The party is on the supply side. I'm saying don't think of

00:59:52.560 --> 00:59:57.280
[Amit Varma]: the supply side, think of the demand side. Till there is demand for it, the supply won't be there.

00:59:57.280 --> 01:00:02.880
[Amit Varma]: When people demand a liberal slash, you know, free thinking party or party that stands for

01:00:02.880 --> 01:00:08.720
[Amit Varma]: individual liberty, like Rajaji and Meenu Mussonni did, then there will be that party. But do people

01:00:08.720 --> 01:00:12.800
[Amit Varma]: demand it? No, those ideas are not in the culture, they're not part of the discourse. Then why should

01:00:12.800 --> 01:00:17.200
[Amit Varma]: that party be there? And many of the people who said that they believed in that and they

01:00:17.200 --> 01:00:22.320
[Amit Varma]: subsequently supported Modi, even when it was obvious that Modi is socialist in his economics

01:00:22.320 --> 01:00:27.440
[Amit Varma]: and authoritarian in his approach to governance in general, and both of which should completely

01:00:27.440 --> 01:00:31.280
[Amit Varma]: be the opposite of what you should stand for. They continued supporting him, they rationalized it,

01:00:31.280 --> 01:00:38.000
[Amit Varma]: which makes me like I, I wrote this piece for Pragati in editorial last year, which I think

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:41.920
[Amit Varma]: is our most read piece ever in terms of views or whatever. It's called Beware of the Useful Idiots.

01:00:41.920 --> 01:00:47.200
[Amit Varma]: So do a search for that, Beware of the Useful Idiots, which talks about exactly this, that all

01:00:47.200 --> 01:00:53.200
[Amit Varma]: of these people gave him legitimacy by sort of pretending that BJP was a great liberal party,

01:00:53.200 --> 01:00:58.560
[Unknown]: which is, of course, a joke. Right. At Anand Hegde on Twitter asks, if you were to create

01:00:58.560 --> 01:01:03.600
[Unknown]: a utopian country, what would be the role of the state in it? Ideally, the role of the state should

01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:09.280
[Amit Varma]: be restricted to protecting rights. But the thing is, and if you're actually interested in this in

01:01:09.280 --> 01:01:14.800
[Amit Varma]: a theoretical sense, then Robert Nozick wrote a great book called Anarchy, State and Utopia.

01:01:14.800 --> 01:01:19.600
[Amit Varma]: And David Friedman wrote a book called The Machinery of Freedom, Milton's son, David

01:01:19.600 --> 01:01:25.600
[Amit Varma]: Friedman. And both of them sort of say that you don't need a government at all. And they tease

01:01:25.600 --> 01:01:29.840
[Amit Varma]: out that idea to his logical conclusions and they show how it's possible to live without a state at

01:01:29.840 --> 01:01:36.080
[Amit Varma]: all. Which I don't agree with because my mind can't wrap itself around it. It's probably a flaw

01:01:36.080 --> 01:01:41.120
[Amit Varma]: on my part, that I think there does need to be some government which protects our rights and so

01:01:41.120 --> 01:01:47.120
[Amit Varma]: on. But it should not do much more than that. But the question is sort of not something I give great,

01:01:47.120 --> 01:01:51.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, not something that the point is, we live in the real world that we live in,

01:01:51.840 --> 01:01:56.480
[Amit Varma]: and all our battles are for more freedom. And we know that more freedom helps. Right. And

01:01:57.280 --> 01:02:00.480
[Amit Varma]: why think of utopia? I mean, utopian thinkers are the most dangerous.

01:02:00.480 --> 01:02:06.240
[Unknown]: Okay. You got a question on Facebook from Darshana Mhatre, where she asked,

01:02:06.240 --> 01:02:10.640
[Unknown]: you expressed your displeasure on demonetization when it was announced. Today, more than a year

01:02:10.640 --> 01:02:14.720
[Unknown]: has passed. Obviously, the cash crunch still remains. And it will only increase with the

01:02:14.720 --> 01:02:19.600
[Unknown]: elections coming in. But otherwise, do you still believe it is too bad a move for the economy?

01:02:19.600 --> 01:02:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Is it too bad a move? It's a disastrous move. I said it at the time I said it repeatedly again

01:02:23.600 --> 01:02:27.360
[Amit Varma]: and again, I stand by it and I'm going to raise my finger and say, I told you so.

01:02:27.360 --> 01:02:31.520
[Amit Varma]: Right. I think I was completely right. I won't give myself much credit for being completely

01:02:31.520 --> 01:02:35.040
[Amit Varma]: right. Because anybody with half a brain could have seen that it was going to be a disaster for

01:02:35.040 --> 01:02:40.640
[Amit Varma]: the economy. And its consequences go far beyond the cash crunch, current cash crunch. It's gonna

01:02:40.640 --> 01:02:46.560
[Amit Varma]: be you know, it destroyed lives. It, it was a humanitarian disaster. And the fact that there

01:02:46.560 --> 01:02:50.400
[Amit Varma]: are some people who call themselves economists who can say, hey, in the long run, it'll help us

01:02:50.400 --> 01:02:55.600
[Amit Varma]: we'll talk about costs and benefits, though, the the presumed benefits may happen to one group of

01:02:55.600 --> 01:02:59.760
[Amit Varma]: people and the costs are on another group of people and it's overwhelmingly hurt the poor.

01:02:59.760 --> 01:03:04.960
[Amit Varma]: I find that repulsive and disgusting. demonetization was a disaster. It was a unilateral

01:03:04.960 --> 01:03:11.200
[Amit Varma]: move by a mad despotic leader who doesn't have a clue about economics. And I condemned it then

01:03:11.200 --> 01:03:15.360
[Amit Varma]: and I condemn it now and my condemning it is really meaningless because it's it's damaged this

01:03:15.360 --> 01:03:21.680
[Unknown]: country. All right. Another question from Twitter from at the luck 365, whose name is the luck

01:03:21.680 --> 01:03:27.440
[Unknown]: comment, also a very regular Cyrus listener. He sent in a question that says just read the WHO's

01:03:27.440 --> 01:03:32.240
[Unknown]: report on air pollution. How do you think our country should lay out a concrete plan on tackling

01:03:32.240 --> 01:03:37.520
[Unknown]: the issue, regulations, penalties, rewards for states, private entities who tackle it, public

01:03:37.520 --> 01:03:44.320
[Amit Varma]: awareness, etc. Okay, so I'm not an expert on the environment or WHO. So I can't go into specifics.

01:03:44.320 --> 01:03:51.040
[Amit Varma]: But I would just say that to identify a problem and say we should do this is a little too

01:03:51.040 --> 01:03:56.400
[Amit Varma]: too simple. What often happens is if you remember, boss, if we I had an episode with Vivek Kaul

01:03:56.400 --> 01:04:03.600
[Amit Varma]: on the pollution in Delhi. And what Vivek pointed out, and this is like really an interesting way

01:04:03.600 --> 01:04:08.000
[Amit Varma]: of thinking about this problem in the political economy. What Vivek pointed out was that look,

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:13.280
[Amit Varma]: the pollution in Delhi is happening because farmers in Punjab are burning rice and it's

01:04:13.280 --> 01:04:18.400
[Amit Varma]: a leftover of that the rice husk or whatever, which they are burning that after you know,

01:04:18.400 --> 01:04:22.000
[Amit Varma]: because they have no other way of getting rid of it. And the fumes because of the way the wind

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:26.480
[Amit Varma]: blows is going to Delhi. Now the thing is, if you one of the reasons that is happening is that rice

01:04:26.480 --> 01:04:31.360
[Amit Varma]: first of all should not be grown in Punjab at all is a point he made, because it's a water intensive

01:04:31.360 --> 01:04:35.840
[Amit Varma]: crop in Punjab is relatively arid. Why is it grown there? Because of government subsidies and

01:04:35.840 --> 01:04:40.080
[Amit Varma]: electricity and these people can just drill out from their bore wells as much water as they need

01:04:40.080 --> 01:04:44.240
[Amit Varma]: to. So that is an unseen effect of a government subsidy, which you see right there, the Delhi

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:50.080
[Amit Varma]: pollution. And if you are going to solve this, how would you solve this? You can't just say that,

01:04:50.080 --> 01:04:54.080
[Amit Varma]: let us make it a crime to burn that because you don't have the state capacity to actually

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:58.080
[Amit Varma]: enforce anything. All that will happen is that the few cops that you have will just get more bribes.

01:04:59.280 --> 01:05:03.840
[Amit Varma]: And it's a political problem because government of Punjab is not going to do anything about it.

01:05:03.840 --> 01:05:08.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, so Kejriwal will go to the Punjab CM and say ki bhai iska kuch karo, but the Punjab CM

01:05:08.640 --> 01:05:13.360
[Amit Varma]: needs those votes. Any party which pisses off the farmers of Punjab is not going to come to power in

01:05:13.360 --> 01:05:18.160
[Amit Varma]: Punjab. So no party is going to do that. How do you solve the problem? Poor Kejriwal in Delhi is,

01:05:18.160 --> 01:05:21.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, putting his muffler and having asthma because of that. But there's nothing he can

01:05:21.840 --> 01:05:27.120
[Amit Varma]: practically do. This is such a huge problem that I can't even think of a possible solution for it,

01:05:27.120 --> 01:05:34.400
[Amit Varma]: even if there's a dictator at the centre and he really won't, you know, how? And a lot of

01:05:34.400 --> 01:05:39.360
[Amit Varma]: governance problems are of this nature. So if you're on the outside and you say that, oh, okay,

01:05:39.360 --> 01:05:43.360
[Amit Varma]: this is happening because farmers are and all of the Delhi pollution isn't because of this. This is

01:05:43.360 --> 01:05:47.360
[Amit Varma]: sort of that takes it beyond the tipping point. But say, okay, ban the farmers from doing that,

01:05:47.360 --> 01:05:53.760
[Amit Varma]: or whatever. But those are very easy answers. Those don't work. No answer. So these are huge

01:05:53.760 --> 01:05:59.040
[Amit Varma]: problems. So for me, having literally no understanding of the environment and what

01:05:59.040 --> 01:06:02.960
[Amit Varma]: the WHO might have done. But when I say no understanding of the environment, I mean,

01:06:02.960 --> 01:06:10.000
[Amit Varma]: the sort of the specific politics as in this case, I really can't say anything. All right.

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:16.240
[Unknown]: Devan Roy, whose Twitter handle is at FA2Lingman asks, why is there no faith in free markets in

01:06:16.240 --> 01:06:21.920
[Amit Varma]: India in spite of its many successes? Because it's counterintuitive. And this is something

01:06:21.920 --> 01:06:27.840
[Amit Varma]: like many of the basic precepts of free markets are counterintuitive. This goes back to what I

01:06:27.840 --> 01:06:33.120
[Amit Varma]: was saying about human nature earlier, that we've evolved, we evolved in prehistoric times,

01:06:33.120 --> 01:06:37.680
[Amit Varma]: our instincts have evolved in prehistoric times. So number one, we thought of the world in zero

01:06:37.680 --> 01:06:42.640
[Amit Varma]: some ways, that if I get something, because those were times of scarcity. So you know,

01:06:42.640 --> 01:06:47.040
[Amit Varma]: there's a dead deer. If I get the deer, the other tribe won't. If the other tribe gets it,

01:06:47.040 --> 01:06:51.520
[Amit Varma]: we won't. You think of the world in zero some ways. So if somebody wins, somebody else loses.

01:06:51.520 --> 01:06:55.040
[Amit Varma]: That's how you think of the economy. So you assume that the solution to poverty must be

01:06:55.040 --> 01:06:59.040
[Amit Varma]: redistribution. You assume that if the rich are getting rich, it can only be if the poor are

01:06:59.040 --> 01:07:04.000
[Amit Varma]: getting poorer, and so on. The positive sumness of things, which is one of the great insights of

01:07:05.360 --> 01:07:10.160
[Amit Varma]: insights about the world is very counterintuitive and very hard to get across. Number one,

01:07:10.160 --> 01:07:16.320
[Amit Varma]: spontaneous order, that's large systems can run by themselves, that languages can evolve and form

01:07:16.320 --> 01:07:21.520
[Amit Varma]: up with sets of rules and all that on their own without a central committee planning it and saying

01:07:21.520 --> 01:07:28.720
[Amit Varma]: this is how you should use a comma. People don't get that. You know, spontaneous order is because

01:07:28.720 --> 01:07:32.720
[Amit Varma]: back in prehistoric times when we evolved, everything was on a scale where you could

01:07:32.720 --> 01:07:37.120
[Amit Varma]: plan it and control it. But large societies are not like that. We run through spontaneous order,

01:07:37.120 --> 01:07:41.680
[Amit Varma]: markets are spontaneous order, languages are spontaneous order. To go back to I pencil by

01:07:41.680 --> 01:07:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Leonard Reed, that is a case of spontaneous order where millions of people combine to produce a

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:50.240
[Amit Varma]: pencil for you, yet you don't know anything about them and they don't know anything about you.

01:07:50.240 --> 01:07:55.760
[Amit Varma]: Deeply counterintuitive, right? So all the ideas of about free markets are extremely

01:07:55.760 --> 01:08:01.120
[Amit Varma]: counterintuitive. Whereas all these sort of command and control socialist ideas that government will

01:08:01.120 --> 01:08:05.760
[Amit Varma]: plan everything and all of that, despite all evidence to the contrary over the last few

01:08:05.760 --> 01:08:10.560
[Amit Varma]: decades of how that works out. They still remain strong in the popular imagination.

