01:19:11.360 --> 01:19:15.520
[Amit Varma]: resource, I look at who owns it. Now it so happens that spectrum in this country is owned by the

01:19:15.520 --> 01:19:19.120
[Amit Varma]: government. It's a different argument whether the government should own spectrum and if not,

01:19:19.120 --> 01:19:22.400
[Amit Varma]: what do you do with it. But given that the government owns a spectrum, they have the right

01:19:22.400 --> 01:19:28.960
[Amit Varma]: to set the conditions on it on how people may use it and so on. And what the net neutrality advocates

01:19:28.960 --> 01:19:32.960
[Amit Varma]: like my friend Nikhil were fighting for is that these are the XYZ are the conditions you should

01:19:32.960 --> 01:19:39.120
[Amit Varma]: set. Others were saying ABC, they have the right to ask for those conditions as an interest group.

01:19:39.120 --> 01:19:44.720
[Amit Varma]: Now, personally, I would just say that every ISP should normally have the right to offer whatever

01:19:44.720 --> 01:19:48.880
[Amit Varma]: it wants to the customers and then you let them compete. Nikhil's point was that there isn't real

01:19:48.880 --> 01:19:53.200
